---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "Why New Managers Say Yes to Everything and Burn Out in 30 Days";
const description = "Saying yes to everything feels like good leadership. It\u2019s how new managers burn out by week three. Here\u2019s how to protect capacity.";
const topic = "Capacity";
const number = "05";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "How New Managers Can Build Authority Without Being Harsh",
    "slug": "/articles/build-authority-as-new-manager/",
    "topic": "Authority"
  },
  {
    "title": "How to Manage Up Without Sounding Insecure as a New Manager",
    "slug": "/articles/manage-up-without-sounding-insecure/",
    "topic": "Managing Up"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/new-managers-say-yes/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/new-managers-say-yes/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>Why New Managers Say Yes to Everything and Burn Out in 30 Days</h1>
<p>Saying yes feels like leadership in month one.</p>
<p>It isn&#x27;t. It is avoidance.</p>
<p>You say yes to your boss, yes to your team, yes to other departments, yes to fixing things that are not yours to fix. By week three you are working late, carrying everyone else&#x27;s work, and wondering why managing feels so heavy.</p>
<p>It feels heavy because you never put anything down.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>You get promoted. You want to prove you deserved it. So you prove it with availability. Open door, always on, always helping.</p>
<p>Your old peers ask for favors, because you used to say yes. You still say yes.</p>
<p>Your boss drops a last-minute request. You say yes, then push it onto your night.</p>
<p>Another team needs “just a quick hand”. Yes.</p>
<p>Your own team brings you problems to solve instead of decisions to approve. You solve them. Yes, yes, yes.</p>
<p>By day 18, your calendar is full, your actual management work is undone, and you are exhausted. You start resenting the team for needing you. But you trained them to need you, by never saying no.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>Your capacity disappears. Management work – planning, feedback, 1:1s, prioritization – gets pushed to evenings. That is not sustainable for 30 days, let alone a year.</p>
<p>Your team gets weaker. Every time you say yes and take the work, they learn not to solve it themselves. You become the bottleneck you complained about.</p>
<p>Priorities blur. When everything is yes, nothing is important. The real deadlines get the same energy as the random favors. Then the real deadlines slip.</p>
<p>You burn out quietly. No one sees it coming, because you kept saying yes with a smile. Then you go flat. Short answers. Missed follow-ups. That is burnout, and the team feels it before you admit it.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is thinking no will cost you respect.</p>
<p>No, delivered clearly, builds respect. Yes, delivered exhausted, destroys it.</p>
<p>New managers confuse responsiveness with responsibility. Answering every Slack in 2 minutes is not leadership. Protecting the team’s focus is.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Use Pause. Priority. Plain no.</p>
<p><strong>1. Pause.</strong> Never say yes in the room. “Let me check capacity and come back to you.” That one sentence buys you space. Most bad yeses happen because you answered under pressure.</p>
<p><strong>2. Priority.</strong> Ask: Does this serve our top 2 priorities this month? If no, it is a no, or a later. If yes, what drops to make room? Every yes is a no to something else. Name what.</p>
<p><strong>3. Plain no.</strong> No apology tour. No five reasons. “We can’t take that on this week. We can revisit in two weeks.” Or: “No, that’s outside our scope. Talk to Ops.” Calm. Short. Done.</p>
<p>Offer an alternative only if you want to. You are allowed a clean no.</p>
<p>Protect three blocks on your calendar every week: planning, 1:1s, and empty space. If someone wants that time, the answer is no. That empty space is what keeps you from burning out.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Instead of:</strong> Boss: “Can you take the Q3 forecast too, just this once?” You: “Yeah sure, no problem!” then working until midnight.</p>
<p><strong>Say:</strong> “Let me check capacity. Right now the team is full with X and Y until Thursday. I can take the forecast Friday, or we can drop Y. Which do you want?”</p>
<p>You did not say no to your boss. You showed the trade-off. That is managing up, and managing capacity.</p>
<p>For peers: “Can’t this week. Backlog is full. Try again next sprint.” That is enough.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Audit your yeses.</strong> Write down everything you said yes to last week. Circle the ones that were not your priority. Those are your leaks.</li>
<li><strong>Install the pause sentence.</strong> “Let me check and come back.” Use it 5 times this week before agreeing to anything.</li>
<li><strong>Block 3 non-negotiable hours.</strong> Planning, 1:1 prep, and one empty hour. Label them. Defend them like a client meeting.</li>
<li><strong>Say 3 clean no’s.</strong> One to a peer, one to a low-priority request, one to yourself – stop taking back IC work you already delegated.</li>
<li><strong>Teach your team to propose, not dump.</strong> When they bring a problem, ask: “What do you recommend?” Stop solving it for them. That one question cuts your workload by 30%.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>Saying yes to everything is not generosity. It is poor prioritization with a nice face.</p>
<p>Your job is not to be available to everyone. Your job is to protect capacity for what matters. That requires no. Calm, early, plain no.</p>
<p>Burnout in month one is preventable. Pause. Priority. Plain no.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
